            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.74"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">74</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    University of Missouri - Columbia
                        <lb/>
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>University of Missouri - Columbia Seal</figDesc>
                        <p>∙ SIGILL ∙ UNIVERSITATIS ∙ MISSOURIEN ∙ MDCCCXXXIX</p>
                    </figure>
                        <lb/>
                    231 Arts &amp; Science 
                    Columbia, Mo. 65201 
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE</hi>
                    Department of English
                        <lb/>
                    Telephone 
                    Area 314 449-9756
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 29, 1972</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you very much for your most thoughtful gift of <hi rend="underline">All is But a Beginning</hi>. I have read it with the same admiration and <unclear><del>D</del><add>d</add></unclear>elight that I have experienced in reading your other works. It is a fine book, rich in color and thought and feeling, and mingling poetic insight with nostalgia and humor. For me it evokes an America that no longer exists except in memory and imagination.</p>
                
                <p>I have always thought of my friendship with you as a rare privilege, and I find that <hi rend="underline">All is But a Beginning has</hi> enriched that by aquainting me with the boy <del>w</del>that you were. I hadn't realized that you lived for a number of years in Kansas City, and I was interested in your experiences there because my family and I <del>li</del><add>mo</add>ved there in 1906 and lived there for many years. For a time we lived at 33rd and Charlotte and at 32nd and Troost, not too far from where you lived.</p> 
                
                <p>We've been interested in your recent appearance on the Dick Cavett show and delighted at the response that you evoked, and we've been equally d<del>l</del><add>e</add>lighted that <hi rend="underline">Black Elk</hi> <del/> <hi rend="underline">Speaks</hi> has been an international best seller.</p> 
                
                <p>Thank you again for the book. We'll be hoping to see you the next time you're in Columbia.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Ed Weatherly</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>Please excuse the typing. My typewr<del>o</del><add>i</add>ter has a bad habit of skipping occasionally.</p> 
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
